<br>
You are referring to the claim that there were 5 active chemical plants found burried near a site the chemical weapons inspectors were at often.  A seperate independant expert said that while the equipment could be used to manufacture chemical weapons, there was no evidence that these had been used to do so or were intended to do so.  The expert said that the equipment was more likely used for other manufacturing processes and was hidded to prevent looting.<br>
<br>
However, that does not extend to the 2 flat bed trucks found that matched the description of those given by the intelligence community before the war.<br>
<br>
The other thing that was found to be not true was a claim that Iraq was trying to buy nuclear materials from south africa.  However, the materials and plans for weapons construction were still found.  The only argument here is that it cannot be proven that it was not from the time before when france gave them a nuclear reactor that they could use to manufacture their own fissable materials.<br>
<br>
Thats your problem, one small part of the evidence is found to be incorrect and suddenly &quot;You know this was all found to be false don't you&quot; is applied to all of it.  At least I'm following it enough to know what was and wasn't.<br>
<br>
The claims made by the anti-war community afterwords are stupid to the point it isn't even funny.  There has been a lot of evidence found.  That doesn't matter to you.  You want a &quot;Smoking Gun&quot;.  More than the &quot;Smoking Gun&quot; - you want the person standing there over a dead corpse with the &quot;Smoking Gun&quot; still in hand.  My point was, you wont be satisfied with any evidence.  You made up your mind long before there even was a war.  So stop trying to ask for &quot;intelligent debate&quot; when all we are going to get from you is worthless retoric.<br>
