Really?  Thats also bullshit.  Now, I hold a bachelors degree in physics, and am currently working on a PhD.  I know very well what you need to manufacture a bomb.  Having that centrifuge is much more important than you think.  I wont go into the details on manufacturing one, but there are 3 main components to a nuclear weapons program<br>
<br>
1) An explosive device capable of initiating the reaction.<br>
   Believe it or not, this is not terribly difficult.  This is mostly a matter of geometry.  However, this can also be the most complicated step.  While there are some simple geometries that would work, finding a SMALL geometry is difficult.<br>
<br>
2) The nuclear material<br>
  The centrifuge is a major part of this.  Normal Uranium is found in 2 isotopes, 235 and 238.  U 235 is MUCH easier to sustain a nuclear reaction in.  Since you are obviously so knowledgable about the reactions invovled, the quick explanation is that the decay chain for 238 has a large amount of neutron capture which tends to stop the reaction.  Because 238 is the dominant isotope in nature, you need either a way to extract 235 from the 238 or you need a special type of reactor designed to change 238 into Plutonium 239.  You can also extract fissable material from other waste products.  Building the centrifuge is a large part of this.<br>
<br>
3) a delivery system<br>
  A suitcase will do depending on the design of the bomb - this is not a problem for anyone.  ICBMs are difficult to manufacture, but you don't need them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Here's the thing, see.. the CIA's assessment is it would take SEVERAL TENS OF THOUSANDS of those centrifuges (as in at least 30,000 of them) a year to produce enough fissile material for 1-2 bombs (provided you had yellowcake)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
