<br>
The two trucks I am referring to had equipment that was only used to manufacture chemicals, not hydrogen.  However, it cannot be proved the chemicals manufactured were biological weapons because the tanks had been chemically scrubbed (ie - the only chemical residue on the tanks were those of common chemical cleaners).  It has been argued the trucks could have been used to produce agricultural chemicals.  However, we can't know one way or the other because of the way they were cleaned.<br>
<br>
Here is a much more recent story on the trucks:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/05/28/sprj.irq.main/index.html" target="top">edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/05/28/sprj.irq.main/index.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
You will note that the claim of these two being hydrogen filling trucks ran counter to evidence at the time.<br>
<br>
Even more recent, the inspections commitee released a statement <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/06/03/sprj.irq.wmd.un.report/index.html" target="top">here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> stating that the trucks in question did not match the photos of any of the equipment certain Iraqi people claimed them to be.<br>
<br>
The most recent position I could find from the CIA is here:<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://edition.cnn.com/2003/US/06/07/cia.mobile.labs/index.html" target="top">edition.cnn.com/2003/US/06/07/cia.mobile.labs/index.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> stating that the person who designed the trucks could identify them from a series of photos saying he built them.<br>
<br>
Now, there are people playing with words in these articles.  You will notice that noone in the UN will say they were.  They say it is &quot;most probably&quot; or &quot;most likely&quot; - but they can't say they are without admitting they were wrong.  However, if the person who designed them and built them says they are, its a pretty good indication they are.<br>
